{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"alias":"coquettish-taurine-pelican","description":"## Context\nRecords rebar's security assurance model (FISMA Moderate target; certification issued from a single Gerrit-authenticated controlled environment, meaning process-followed + no-blocking-issues, NOT a correctness guarantee) and frames the identity/op-cert security assessment findings as five ACCEPTED limitations (L1 key-validity-rests-on-access-control, L2 no-transparency-log, L3 TOFU-authorship, L4 single-environment/no-threshold, L5 process-not-correctness), each with its bounding control, authority tier, and tracked deferred-hardening idea ticket. Benchmarked against gittuf/TUF/Sigstore/in-toto/SLSA/RFC 8725/NIST SSDF.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `docs/adr/0046-security-posture-and-accepted-limitations.md` exists and is accepted, stating the FISMA-Moderate target and the meaning of certification.\n- [ ] Each of the five findings is framed as an accepted limitation with a bounding control + authority tier (never as an unmitigated threat).\n- [ ] Deferred-hardening items reference the tracked idea tickets (2422, 4e1d, 5100).\n- [ ] The ADR lands on main via Gerrit (Verified +1, LLM-Review +1).","id":"5f30-b276-923e-4cf2","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"task","title":"docs: ADR 0046 — security posture, assurance model, and accepted limitations"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1783965733679739001,"uuid":"01cf1e46-82d7-4ee2-90cc-188ae6df071e"}